ceased","1398–1463":"1398–1463","1441–1485":"1441–1485","1337–1384":"1337–1384","1347–1387":"1347–1387","1374":"1374","1384":"1384","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","18 June 1463":"18 June 1463","1337":"1337","1425":"1425","1347":"1347","1455":"1455","1387":"1387","1398":"1398","1430":"1430","1441":"1441","1463":"1463","1485":"1485","27 October 1384":"27 October 1384","about 1440":"about 1440","7 August 1387":"7 August 1387","Tehidy, Cornwall, England":"Tehidy, Cornwall, England","Yarnscombe, Devonshire, England":"Yarnscombe, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bassett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from Old French <i>basset</i> ‘of low stature’, a diminutive of <i>basse</i> ‘low, short’, either a nickname for a short person or a status name for someone of humble origins.","Altered form of French   Bessette   1 or <b>Besset</b> (see   Bessette   2).","History: William Bassett (<i>c.</i> 1598–1667) came to Plymouth, MA, from Kent, England, in the 1620s; <i>c.</i> 1650 he moved to Duxbury and subesequently to Bridgewater. He had many prominent descendants, among them one of the earliest families on Martha's Vineyard. — The surname <i>Bassett</i> of French origin (see 2 above) is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America."],"variants":[{"name":"Bessette","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Marcel, Armand, Adrien, Normand, Alphonse, Lucien, Cecile, Herve, Jacques, Laurent, Aime.","French: topographic name designating a small wood of birches, from Occitan <i>bès</i> ‘birch tree’ (see   Besse  ), or a habitational name from (La) Bessette, the name of several places in the southern part of France.","Alternatively, an altered form of French <b>Besset</b>: topographic name, a cognate of 1 above. Altered ending reflects the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":8,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":81,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Bassett I was born in 1374, in Tehidy, Cornwall, England, his father, William de Basset III, was 37 and his mother, Margaret Fleming, was 28. He married Joan Beaumont in 1430, in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom. He died on 18 June 1463, in his hometown, at the age of 89."},"et":{"1374–18 June 1463":"1374–18. juuni 1463","1372–Female":"1372–Surnud","1374–1463":"1374–1463","1425–Female":"1425–Surnud","1398–1463":"1398–1463","1441–1485":"1441–1485","1337–1384":"1337–1384","1347–1387":"1347–1387","1374":"1374","1384":"1384","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","18 June 1463":"18. juuni 1463","1337":"1337","1425":"1425","1347":"1347","1455":"1455","1387":"1387","1398":"1398","1430":"1430","144